<p><strong>What an investor needs is the ability to correctly evaluate selected businesses.</strong> Note that word "selected": You don't have to be an expert on every company, or even many. You only have to be able to evaluate companies within your circle of competence. The size of that circle is not very important; knowing its boundaries, however, is vital.</p>



<p>For example, I have no competence in evaluating pharmaceutical companies, optical electronics companies, or coal companies. Within the pharmaceutical industry, I couldn't have told you which of the 300 companies in the field had the best chance to prosper. But I could have told you in 20 seconds — and with a high degree of conviction — that Procter & Gamble was a better business than any of them. To be a successful investor you must firmlygrid deals that are outside your circle of competence. That sounds easy, but it is not.</p>



